title: (Minor) flaws regarding standard compliance in Reference models
body:
Hey guys!
I loosely follow your work for some years and I think its quite impressive what you have achieved so far and I really like it that you are still committed to improve the interoperability of BPMN tools.

As mentioned in #709 I was analysing the reference models you created with a research prototype of a BPMN compliance checking tool that is rather nitpicky regarding standard compliance. This tool reported some (minor) flaws in the reference models (and partially a lot more problems in the models created by the tested tools :wink:):

- `A.2.1.bpmn`, l. 119, 145, 154, 163 and 172: These lines contain a `formalExpression` without any body. According to the specification this should not be allowed. See spec 8.3.6 p. 86, Table 8.43: cardinality of "body": 
![grafik](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/676652/21904079/b5679944-d902-11e6-98c3-fca247d7be42.png)
However, I do not really get the meaning of the highlighted text. Can you explain this to me?

- ` B.2.0.bpmn`
  - l. 363: The should be not `ioSpecification` - or at least no `dataInput` for a `subProcess`. This stated in chapter 10.3.1., p. 211: 
![grafik](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/676652/21904461/00b70c94-d904-11e6-8c82-2d87f8223cbf.png)
  - l. 361 and l. 454: Link Event correlation using names - this is at least questionable, but I've seen that this has already been discussed in #141 

- `C.1.0.bpmn` (l. 534) and also `C.3.0.bpmn` (l.73 + l.449): The processes contained here are marked as `executable`, but the `messageEventDefinition`s used there do not contain an `operationRef`. This violates the specification: 
![grafik](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/676652/21904889/8225187e-d905-11e6-91f2-3044b66db41b.png) 
(Table 10.99, p. 271)
I think in practice this attribute is not used - let alone required - by any of the BPMN engines on the market. Maybe an aspect to considered for the RTF?

What do you think of those reported problems?

Best regards
Matthias

title: Participant missing in collaboration
body:
The model A.4.0 has two processes, obviously collaborating. The collaboration element has only one participant. The specification has 3 relevant statements to be considered for this issue:
- One, and only one, Pool in a diagram MAY be presented without a boundary. If there is more than one Pool in the diagram, then the remaining Pools MUST have a boundary
- A Collaboration can contain two (2) or more Pools (i.e., Participants). However, a Process that represents the work performed from the point of view of the modeler or the modelers organization can be considered internal and is NOT REQUIRED to be surrounded by the boundary of the Pool, while the other Pools in the Diagram MUST have their boundary (see Figure 9.5).
- "A Pool is the graphical representation of a Participant in a Collaboration."

According to the aforementioned statements, the collaboration element should have two participants, but no BPMNShape representing the second participant as the process is considered internal.

title: [Execution - 2015 demo] Alternative version of C.1.0 for the demo
body:
I would like to submit for discussion an alternate version of the C.1.0 model

This model presents no W4 specific mecanism and only use standard BPMN mecanism such as Xsd for types definition and XPATH for formal expression and is fully executable, according to the specification.

It introduce Data Objects 'approved' and 'clarified' used to evaluate the Condition Expressions using XPATH. These Data Objects respectively reference Item Definitions ref 'xsdBool' and 'xsdString' using xsd structure reference corresponding to boolean and string. The xsd type definition are imported into the Definitions using the standard import mecanism

Finally 'Archive invoice' Service Task implementation has been set to '##unspecified' so each vendor can choose how to run the associated service

title: [Execution - 2015 demo] Conditions on Sequence Flow outgoing of Gateway with id "invoice_approved"
body:
The Sequence Flow labeled "yes" (id="invoiceApproved"), outgoing of Gateway "Invoice approved" (id="invoice_approved"), has the following Condition Expression :

```
<conditionExpression xsi:type="tFormalExpression" id="sid-0ed8a0cb-f28a-4689-bbd8-77dafd0ccfa0">${approved}</conditionExpression>
```

How is this expression to be resolved from a standard point of view ? What is 'approved' suppose to be since it does not seems to be a DataObject or DataStore ?
If we look at the expression language attribute of the definitions, we have

```
expressionLanguage="http://www.w3.org/1999/XPath".
```

This means that the expression language used to resolve formal expressions should be XPATH. I thing XPATH is a good choice for the demo since it should be supported by BPMN implementors (according to chapter 10.3.3 of the spec), but if we are to use XPATH the expression should be :

```
<conditionExpression xsi:type="tFormalExpression" id="sid-0ed8a0cb-f28a-4689-bbd8-77dafd0ccfa0">getDataObject('approved')</conditionExpression>
```

where 'approved' is a DataObject of boolean type. We could use the default type language (Table 8.1 page 53 of the spec) to define the type of this DataObject so it would be http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema:boolean

ps : The same observation can be done for the Sequence Flow with id 'invoiceNotApproved'.

title: Test Case C.1.0: User Tasks with incoming/outgoing Message Flows
body:
In the process model there is a user task with one outgoing message flow and one outgoing message flow.
I believe this is not conform with the BPMN specification (and in particular, the execution semantics part). The BPMN2 specification says:
"User Task: Upon activation, the User Task is distributed to the assigned person or group of people. When the work has been done, the User Task completes."
Although the BPMN metamodel allows such a constellation - Message Flows can theoretically be connected to any type of Tasks - still the (execution) semantics of incoming and outgoing Message Flows for User Tasks is not defined.
So I would argue that the adopted process model is not a valid BPMN model.

Use case where I detected an interchange incompatibility:
If no conditionExpression set on a Sequence Flow and the Sequence Flow is not marked as default on outgoing reference of Task/Gateways, the Sequence Flow is  a "normal" Sequence Flow. title: Proposal for relaxed data constraint in non WS-* serviceTask
body:
This statement is made for service tasks on p158 (PDF p.188): 

```
         "In addition the following constraints are introduced 
         when the Service Task references an Operation: The Service Task has 
         exactly one inputSet and at most one outputSet. It has a single Data 
         Input with an ItemDefinition equivalent to the one defined by the 
         Message referenced by the inMessageRef attribute of the associated 
         Operation. If the Operation defines output Messages, the Service Task 
         has a single Data Output that has an ItemDefinition equivalent to the 
         one defined by the Message referenced by the outMessageRef attribute 
         of the associated Operation."
```

For RESTful implementations it turns out this is an unnecessary constraint so in order to minimise the burden for such implementations we propose the following change to the text: 

After 

```
         "...when the Service Task references an Operation: ..." 
```

add 

```
         " and when the implementation attribute of the Service Task is set to '##WebService'"
```

title: dataOutputAssociation from startDataOutput to taskDataInput
body:
### A.1.2 reference visualization

![15cb0d1e-db7e-11e3-8de3-aff1969b665e](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5450234/3029638/867caf8c-e037-11e3-8242-5493208d08c8.png)
### A.1.2 reference serialization

StartEvent (I omitted parts, just to focus on the problem)

``` xml
<semantic:startEvent name="Start Event" id="startEvent">
    ...
    <semantic:dataOutput name="Start Event Data Output" id="startEventDataOutput" itemSubjectRef="serviceInput" />
    <semantic:dataOutputAssociation id="startEventDataOutputAssociation">
        <semantic:sourceRef>startEventDataOutput</semantic:sourceRef>
        <semantic:targetRef>dataInputTask1</semantic:targetRef>
    </semantic:dataOutputAssociation>
    <semantic:outputSet>
        <semantic:dataOutputRefs>startEventDataOutput</semantic:dataOutputRefs>
    </semantic:outputSet>
    ...
</semantic:startEvent>
```

UserTask

``` xml
<semantic:userTask implementation="##unspecified" name="Task 1" id="task1" startQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" completionQuantity="1">
    ...
    <semantic:ioSpecification>
        <semantic:dataInput name="Data Input Task 1" id="dataInputTask1" itemSubjectRef="serviceInput" />
        ...
        <semantic:inputSet>
            <semantic:dataInputRefs>dataInputTask1</semantic:dataInputRefs>
        </semantic:inputSet>
        ...
    </semantic:ioSpecification>
    ...
</semantic:userTask>
```
### Problem

Please correct me if I am wrong. In a DataOutputAssociation the targetRef has to reference to an itemAwareElement in the current scope of the process. The _dataInputTask1_ is the dataInput of the UserTask. During the execution of the _startEventDataOutputAssociation_ the UserTask is not in the current scope of the process, it has not yet received the execution token. So it is not possible to have the dataInput of the task as targetRef of the dataOutputAssociation of the startEvent.
### Proposed solution

Add a dataObject in the process to transfer the content of the message from the startEvent to the task.
_Technically_
- add a dataObject in the process
- edit the current startDataOutputAssociation targetRef to reference the dataObject
- add a userTaskDataInputAssociation with sourceRef referencing the dataObject and targetRef referencing the userTaskDataInput.
### Correlated Problem

Symmetrically, this issue affect also the UserTask that is connected to the endEvent.

title: Connecting a Message via an association to a MessageFlow?
body:
I got a question regarding a special modelling style. The question is how do you connect the message decorator to a message flow correctly. 

First option would be to put it directly on the message flow as shown in the BPMN 2.0 spec on page 411 (see MessageFlow_V1 below)

Second option would be to connect the Message decorator via an undirected association to the message flow (see MessageFlow_V2 below). 

I am wondering now if the MessageFlow_V2 example is actually valid BPMN 2.0 and interchangeable with the XML serialization.

From my point of view it is no valid BPMN 2.0 as Message is no FlowElement and therefore cannot be referenced by the BPMNShape element in the BPMNDI part which makes it impossible to place the Message decorator to any arbitrary position as done in MessageFlow_V2.

Additionally there is no BPMNShape listed in the spec for the single message symbol (table 12.35 on page 411). Sections BPMNShape (Section 12.3.2) and BPMNEdge (Section 12.3.3) also supports this. So I would say the meta model of BPMN 2.0 does not support this.
